  "prompt": "What hand drawn anime is out there?",
  "response": "Ah, you're looking for anime that was primarily hand-drawn! That's a good question, as CGI has become increasingly prevalent. While virtually *all* anime has *some* digital components these days (especially for coloring and post-processing), I'll focus on anime where the core animation and keyframes were primarily created using traditional hand-drawn techniques.\n\nKeep in mind that even \"hand-drawn\" anime will often incorporate some digital cleanup, compositing, and effects. The line between purely hand-drawn and digitally assisted is often blurred.\n\nHere are some examples, broken down by era and with some notes on their production styles:\n\n**Classic Era (Pre-2000s - When Hand-Drawn Animation Was the Norm):**\n\n*   **Most anime from this era!** Seriously, almost everything before the widespread adoption of digital animation was primarily hand-drawn. The limitations of the medium also give many of these series a unique charm.\n\n    *   **Examples:**\n        *   *Akira* (1988):  A landmark film known for its incredibly detailed animation and complex movement, all achieved through traditional techniques.\n        *   *Ghost in the Shell* (1995): Another visually stunning film that pushed the boundaries of hand-drawn animation.\n        *   *Neon Genesis Evangelion* (1995-1996): Famous for its distinctive character designs and impactful visual storytelling.\n        *   *Cowboy Bebop* (1998):  Stylish and action-packed, with fluid animation and memorable characters.\n        *   Studio Ghibli films (like *My Neighbor Totoro*, *Spirited Away*, *Princess Mononoke*): Ghibli is renowned for its commitment to traditional animation techniques.\n        *   *Dragon Ball* and *Dragon Ball Z*: Early instalments of this show are completely hand-drawn.\n\n**Transitional Era (2000s - As Digital Techniques Became More Common):**\n\n*   This is where things get a bit trickier, as many anime started blending hand-drawn and digital methods.\n\n    *   **Examples:**\n        *   *Millennium Actress* (2001): Directed by Satoshi Kon, this film blends reality and memory through beautifully animated sequences.\n        *   *Perfect Blue* (1998): Another Satoshi Kon film, known for its psychological depth and visually striking animation.\n        *   *FLCL* (2000-2001): A frenetic and experimental series with a unique visual style.\n        *   *Fullmetal Alchemist* (2003): While later seasons used more digital techniques, the original *Fullmetal Alchemist* series relied heavily on hand-drawn animation.\n        *   *Paprika* (2006): A visual masterpiece from Satoshi Kon, pushing the boundaries of dreamlike imagery and animation.\n        *   *The Girl Who Leapt Through Time* (2006): A coming-of-age story with charming character animation.\n\n**Modern Era (2010s - Present):**\n\n*   Finding *purely* hand-drawn anime in this era is very difficult. Almost everything will have digital elements. However, some studios prioritize traditional techniques and keep digital assistance to a minimum.\n\n    *   **Examples (These will likely have digital assistance, but prioritize hand-drawn animation):**\n        *   *In This Corner of the World* (2016): A critically acclaimed film that uses a distinct, almost watercolor-like animation style.\n        *   *Ride Your Wave* (2019): This film from Masaaki Yuasa (director of *Devilman Crybaby*) is known for its fluid and expressive animation.\n        *   *Children of the Sea* (2019): Visually stunning and deeply atmospheric, this film features beautiful hand-drawn backgrounds and character animation.\n        *   *Belle* (2021): While also incorporating CGI, *Belle* still has beautiful hand-drawn animation for the protagonist.\n        *   *Keep Your Hands Off Eizouken!* (2020): The story of a group of high school students making anime, it notably has a unique art style and great animation. It is directed by Masaaki Yuasa.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Backgrounds:** Even in primarily hand-drawn anime, backgrounds are often created using digital painting or 3D modeling (especially in more recent productions).  However, some studios (like Ghibli) still create many of their backgrounds using traditional painting techniques.\n*   **In-Between Animation:** This is the process of creating the frames that fill in the gaps between the keyframes, creating the illusion of movement. While keyframes might be hand-drawn, in-between animation can sometimes be outsourced and may involve digital assistance.\n*   **\"Digital Animation\" Doesn't Always Mean Bad:** Digital tools can be used to enhance and streamline the animation process, and many modern anime look absolutely stunning. It's more about the *philosophy* of the production and the extent to which hand-drawn techniques are prioritized.\n*   **The Future:**  There's a resurgence of interest in traditional animation techniques, and some studios are experimenting with ways to blend the best of both worlds.\n\n**How to Tell (Sometimes):**\n\n*   **Look for a \"softer\" or more textured look:** Hand-drawn animation often has a slightly less \"perfect\" appearance, with subtle variations in line weight and color.\n*   **Pay attention to fluid movement:** Hand-drawn animation can achieve a level of fluidity and expressiveness that is sometimes difficult to replicate with CGI.\n*   **Check the credits:** While not always conclusive, the animation studio's website or interviews with the creators might provide information about their production methods.\n\nUltimately, the best way to appreciate hand-drawn anime is to watch it and experience the artistry for yourself!\n",
